Goals are to get to know what are the main aspects of international protection of human rights: where in this system is situated the European Convention on Human Rights, what is the position of European Convention on Human Rights in the legal systems of  Convention member states, in parfticular in Estonia; how does the European Court of Human Rights work:  structure and functions of this Court; main principles that the Court applies in its work. The course will also give an overview of the most important cases of the European Court of Human Rights and analyse recent case-law, as well as the case law connected to Estonia. It wll also be explained how the member states, including Estonia have implemented the decisions and judgments of the European Court of Human Rights. At the end of the course a short overview of the "Bermuda triangle" in the protection of fundmanetal rights: the Estonian Constitution, the European Convention on Human Rights and the Charter of Fundamental Rights of the European Union will be discussed.Objectives/eesmärkid:  Main goals are: to learn and understand the principal aspects of the international protection of human rights based on the practice of the protection system of the European Convention on Human Rights. To navigate in the functions and case law of the European Court of Human Rights and to study the relations between European human rights protection and national (Estonian) law.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  The student who has passed the course: -- understands the role and nature of human rights -- knows the historical development and theoretical bases of human rights -- names essential human rights instruments -- describes and compares principal protective mechanisms for human rights -- explains and interprets the content of core human rights and relevant practice
